  "subtitle": "[ASSET: right | VmaMoment | width=27%] This month's VMA goes to [LINK:1962:FF_12|FF #12], where on its page 8, General Ross explains to the Invisible Girl:\n[BR]\n[BR] \"Miss Storm, a pretty young lady can <i>always</i> be of help -- just by keeping the men's morale up!\"\n[BR]\n[BR] ...to which Reed actually replies:&nbsp; \"That's just the way <i>we</i> feel about Sue, General!\"\n[BR]\n[BR] [SPAN: fontsize=small; fonttype=italic; text=(Holy cow!)]",
  "review_text": "[DEVNOTE: *** SUMMARY_BEGIN ***\n*** THIS MONTH ***7 graded stories over 6 issues...TOTAL WEIGHT: 4 grade character issue   weight 9.2   asm       ASM #1  0.5 8.0   iron      TOS #39 0.5 7.0   asm       ASM #1  0.5 6.5   ff        FF #12  1.0 3.0   torch     ST #106 0.5 2.0   thor      JIM #89 0.5 1.8   ant       TTA #41 0.55.50*** LAST MONTH ***7 graded stories over 5 issues...TOTAL WEIGHT: 3.5 grade character issue   weight 8.0   ff        FF #11  0.5 6.0   ff        FF #11  0.5 5.5   thor      JIM #88 0.5 3.5   torch     ST #105 0.5 3.0   ant       TTA #40 0.5 1.5   hulk      HULK #5 0.5 1.0   hulk      HULK #5 0.54.07\n*** SUMMARY_END ***]\n\nThis last month of the year brought 7 graded stories across 6 issues ([LINK:1962:ASM_1_asm1|ASM #1] carried two), landing at a weighted average of [SPAN: severity=info; fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text=5.50] -- almost a point-and-a-half better than last month.\n\nIt was a true rags‑or‑riches stretch:&nbsp; Spider‑Man, the Fantastic Four, and the newly minted Iron Man pulled the line upward, while the solo Human Torch, Ant‑Man, and even Thor dragged things back down to Earth.\n\nEven with that dead weight at the tail end, the month still delivered a solidly readable result, if ultimately below mid‑grade.&nbsp; With Stan effectively writing everything, you can feel the strain -- a reminder of the risks of having one person shoulder nearly all the story planning.\n\nOn the brighter side, closing out the year with two new headlining heroes -- Spider‑Man and Iron Man -- injects real energy into the line‑up.&nbsp; Marvel ends the year not just with more titles, but with more <i>possibility</i>.",
  "letters_page": "[HANG0] * The additions of Spider-Man and Iron Man to the regular monthly fold <i>has</i> to qualify as this month's biggest highlight\n[HANG0] * Introduction of the Chameleon, J. Jonah Jameson and the Acrobat rounded out the less notable debuts.\n[HANG0] * Two Marvel crossovers on the same day, both featuring the FF, serve notice that these characters share a universe.\n[HANG0] * Elimination of the notion that Johnny Storm has a secret identity -- an incredibly silly idea if ever there was one.\n[HANG0] * The character of Jameson is particularly fascinating and unique:&nbsp; an editor of a major newspaper with a vendetta against a costumed hero.\n\n[DEVNOTE: *** INTRODUCTION_BEGIN ***\nNotes | first | villain | Thug Thatchar (Andrew Thatcher)\nNotes | first | Ruby (Ruby Mortensen, Thug's girlfriend)\nNotes | first | villain | death | Kulla\nJ. Jonah Jameson | villain | Milestone: (first)\nJohn Jameson | Milestone: (first)\nChameleon | villain | Milestone: (first)\nNotes | first | villain | Wrecker (Karl Kort)\nNotes | first | villain | Torrid Twosome\nNotes | first | villain | Acrobat (Carl Zante)\nIron Man | Milestone: (first), (origin)\nNotes | first | Professor Yinsen (Ho Yinsen)\nNotes | first | villain | death | Wong-Chu\nNotes | first | villain | Viet Cong\n*** INTRODUCTION_END ***]\n[DEVNOTE: *** HIGHLIGHTS_BEGIN ***]\n[HANG0] * A mobster, a skyscraper, and a bucket of hot rivets walk into a Thor comic... and Odin's basically on standby.\n[HANG0] * Ant‑Man faces a disposable warlord, and I'm left feeling like the only one who served a prison sentence.\n[HANG0] * Spider‑Man stops a space disaster and still gets branded a menace.\n[HANG0] * The Marvel Universe expands to include Spider-Man... and the Chameleon just disguises himself as a major threat.\n[HANG0] * A historic first Thing/Hulk clash... and a mid‑issue comedy detour that refuses to stay in its lane.\n[HANG0] * The Acrobat tricks Johnny, the FF shrug, and the story concludes with a weary RESET!\n[HANG0] * Iron Man's debut turns survival into a <b>forged</b> and quietly <b>riveting</b> sentence -- and it hits hard.\n[DEVNOTE: *** HIGHLIGHTS_END ***]",
  "ownership": "The start of 1963 promises these juicy adventures:\n\n[HANG0] * FF head to the Moon\n[HANG0] * Human Torch vs Sub-Mariner\n[HANG0] * The new Iron Man decides he looks a bit frightening\n[HANG0] * And we finally get to bid farewell to the Hulk's abysmal magazine!\n\nBut first, we pause to celebrate Longbox Playback's first <b>End-of-Year Awards</b> -- a milestone worth the wait."
}